jects among remote and largely non-literate peoples around the globe. Recording their dreams, stories, and innermost thoughts in a vast database, Kaplan envisioned future researchers accessing the data through the cutting-edge Readex machine. Almost immediately, however, technological developments and the obsolescence of the theoretical framework rendered the project irrelevant, and eventually it was forgotten.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDreamsxData processingxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychologyxData processingxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychologyxResearchxHistoryy20th century. 0aSociologyxData processingxHistoryy20th century. 0aSociologyxResearchxHistoryy20th century. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030020952540uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030021664640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300216646423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300216646/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY